    <h2>3. Project Directory Structure</h2>
    <p>The code architecture follows a structured separation of concerns pattern to ensure modularity and ease of maintenance:</p>
    
    <pre>
lib/
├── auth/
│   ├── firebase_load_check_screen.dart   # Loader during Firebase loading
│   ├── forgot_password_screen.dart       # Password reset submission UI
│   ├── login_screen.dart                  # User authentication screen
│   ├── signup_screen.dart                 # Account creation screen with role choice
│   ├── simple_preload_screen.dart         # Transition preloader before dashboard
│   └── start_page.dart                    # Welcome lander screen (EduLK logo)
│
├── core/
│   ├── app_colors.dart                   # Global theme color tokens (Blue Palette)
│   ├── dashboard_wrapper.dart            # Handles routing check (Admin vs User)
│   └── firebase_options.dart             # Configuration mapping for Firebase platforms
│
├── models/
│   └── user_model.dart                   # Data modeling for Firebase user profiles
│
├── screens/
│   ├── admin_dashboard.dart              # Specialized Admin settings panel
│   └── user_dashboard.dart               # User profile page
│
├── auth_service.dart                     # Detached service layer for auth operations
└── main.dart                             # Starts the application and configures local timezone
    </pre>

    <h2>4. Architectural Workflow &amp; Router Control</h2>
    <p>The application employs a stream listener inside the entry file to monitor authentication state transitions. Once authenticated, the <code>DashboardWrapper</code> executes a Firestore lookup to retrieve the current user's role metadata.</p>
    
    <pre>
1. main() Initializes -> Configures TimeZone (Asia/Colombo) -> Initializes Firebase.
2. AuthWrapper listens to authStateChanges Stream.
   ├── ConnectionState.waiting -> Shows FirebaseLoadCheckScreen
   ├── Snapshot has no data    -> Redirects to StartPage
   └── Snapshot has user data  -> Redirects to SimplePreloadScreen -> DashboardWrapper
3. DashboardWrapper retrieves current Firebase UID.
   └── Reads Firestore collection `/users/{uid}`.
       ├── role == "admin"     -> Launches AdminDashboard
       └── role == "user"      -> Launches UserDashboard
    </pre>

    <h2>5. Database Schema Definition (Cloud Firestore)</h2>
    <p>The app stores non-credential user records in Firestore under the <code>users</code> collection. Each record maps directly to the user's Auth <code>uid</code>:</p>
    
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Field Name</th>
                <th>Data Type</th>
                <th>Database Purpose</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><code>uid</code></td>
                <td>String</td>
                <td>Primary key corresponding to the Firebase Auth ID.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><code>name</code></td>
                <td>String</td>
                <td>The full name inputted by the user during signup.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><code>email</code></td>
                <td>String</td>
                <td>Primary communication email address.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><code>nic</code></td>
                <td>String</td>
                <td>National Identity Card number for identity verification.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><code>mobile</code></td>
                <td>String</td>
                <td>Mobile telephone contact details.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><code>role</code></td>
                <td>String</td>
                <td>Defines privileges (restricted options include "admin" or "user").</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><code>profileImageUrl</code></td>
                <td>String</td>
                <td>The network URL retrieved from Cloudinary after uploading.</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>6. Core Technical Code Components</h2>
    <h3>6.1 Firestore Profile Serializer</h3>
    <p>The model class <code>AppUser</code> converts Firestore data mapping keys into structured Dart objects and vice versa:</p>
    <pre>
class AppUser {
  final String uid;
  final String email;
  final String name;
  final String nic;
  final String mobile;
  final String role;

  AppUser({
    required this.uid,
    required this.email,
    required this.name,
    required this.nic,
    required this.mobile,
    required this.role,
  });

  Map&lt;String, dynamic&gt; toMap() {
    return {
      'uid': uid,
      'email': email,
      'name': name,
      'nic': nic,
      'mobile': mobile,
      'role': role,
    };
  }

  factory AppUser.fromMap(String uid, Map&lt;String, dynamic&gt; map) {
    return AppUser(
      uid: uid,
      email: map['email'] ?? '',
      name: map['name'] ?? '',
      nic: map['nic'] ?? '',
      mobile: map['mobile'] ?? '',
      role: map['role'] ?? 'user',
    );
  }
}
    </pre>

    <h3>6.2 Direct Cloudinary HTTP Upload</h3>
    <p>To keep the application thin, profile photos are posted to Cloudinary via a direct HTTP Multipart Post request. The Cloudinary server returns a JSON payload containing the public secure URL:</p>
    <pre>
Future&lt;String?&gt; _uploadToCloudinary(File file) async {
  final uri = Uri.parse("https://api.cloudinary.com/v1_1/dqeptzlsb/image/upload");
  final request = http.MultipartRequest("POST", uri);
  
  request.fields['upload_preset'] = 'flutter_mediq_upload';
  request.files.add(await http.MultipartFile.fromPath('file', file.path));

  final response = await request.send();
  if (response.statusCode == 200) {
    final responseData = await response.stream.toBytes();
    final responseString = String.fromCharCodes(responseData);
    final jsonMap = jsonDecode(responseString);
    return jsonMap['secure_url']; // Remote URL
  }
  return null;
}
    </pre>
